Patch Set 1:

Christoph, I don't really know what's correct or not here in this implementation that you contributed.  Why set this environment variable at all?   

I get the sense that the user sets this in their environment and that we should not override it:

https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/260601/understanding-setting-up-different-input-methods

Or maybe we should use this to determine the value:  

String gtkImModule = System.getenv("GTK_IM_MODULE");

But then, if it's already in the environment why set it in the desktop file?

Please advise.

the problem is that eclipse behaves very sloppy if this is not set (eg flickering) see:

https://git.eclipse.org/c/platform/eclipse.platform.swt.git/commit/?id=ee007550340c5848c429928a6b9f5903f91073bd

I think setting it in the desktop file to make sure Eclipse is working regardless of system setting might be a good idea as it seems SWT is supposed to not work well with other settings.

It seems the parser had existing functionality to parse either "\|" or "\" characters so we could handle the case where it is escaped. It seems this type of escaping only used to be required in certain contexts.

In contrast to this, we would only ever write in the "|" character and never the escaped version "\|" which is where the table rendering bug comes from.

I think we should move towards always escaping the character to be more strict and this is what I have implemented in the code.

Following on for this is the result of the issue with the exclamation character "!". Here we did not have support for parsing the escaped version and Cloud Jira now seems to always escape this but will render it correctly (for obvious use cases anyway...) correctly without the escape.

I do think it is slightly overstrict but we should be default escape the character here as well.
